<h1>12.802: Problem Set 3</h1>

<hr style="width: 60em;">

<h3>Problem 1</h3>

<p>
<b>(a)</b> We want to derive an approximation for the potential vorticity of a 1-layer homogenous model on the $\beta-$plane a constant depth $H$ in the absence of external forcing (i.e. it is conserved):
\begin{equation}
	\frac{\textrm{D}}{\textrm{D}t}\left[\frac{f + \zeta}{h}\right] = 0,
\end{equation}
where we define the following terms:
\begin{align}
	\zeta &= \frac{\partial v}{\partial x} - \frac{\partial u}{\partial y}, \\
	f &= f_0 + \beta y, \\
	h &= H + \eta,
\end{align}
and the derivative is the material derivative, defined as $\partial_t + \underline{u}\cdot\nabla$.
To derive this approximation, we first note and suppose a few things:
\begin{align}
	|\eta| &\ll |H|, \\
	|\zeta| &\ll |f_0|, \\
	|\beta y| &\ll |f_0|.
\end{align}
We further remember the following useful Taylor expansion:
\begin{equation}
	\frac{1}{1 - x} = \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} x^n.
\end{equation}
So, we first can see:
\begin{equation}
	\frac{f + \zeta}{h} = \frac{\zeta + f}{H}\frac{1}{\left(1 + \eta / H\right)}.
\end{equation}
Then, we can apply the Taylor expansion from above to the second fraction and only consider first order terms, which gives:
\begin{equation}
	\frac{\zeta + f}{H}\left(1 - \frac{\eta}{H}\right) = \frac{1}{H}\left(\zeta + f - \zeta \frac{\eta}{H} - f_0\frac{\eta}{H} - \beta y \frac{\eta}{H}\right).
\end{equation}
By the suppositions above, we can reduce this to:
\begin{equation}
	\frac{1}{H}\left(\zeta + f - f_0 \frac{\eta}{H}\right).
\end{equation}
As $1 / H$ and $f_0$ are constants, by plugging in the above equation to the material derivative, we can simplify this expression to:
\begin{equation}
	\frac{\textrm{D}}{\textrm{D}t}\left[\zeta + \beta y - f_0 \frac{\eta}{H}\right] = 0.
\end{equation}
</p>
<p>
<b>(b)</b> We now want to linearize the equation from above about a rest state, i.e. $\overline{\underline{u}} = \overline{\eta} = 0$ via perturbation quantities of order $\epsilon \ll 1$, i.e.:
\begin{align}
	u\left(x, y, t\right) &= \epsilon u'\left(x, y, t\right), \\
	v\left(x, y, t\right) &= \epsilon v'\left(x, y, t\right), \\
	\eta\left(x, y, t\right) &= \epsilon \eta'\left(x, y, t\right).
\end{align}
Plugging these quantities  

</p>

